{{Infobox SCOTUS case |Litigants=Busey v. District of Columbia |ArgueDate=June 1 |ArgueYear=1943 |DecideDate=June 14 |DecideYear=1943 |FullName=Busey, et al. v. District of Columbia |USVol=319 |USPage=579 |ParallelCitations=63 S. Ct. 1277; 87 [[L. Ed.]] 1598; 1943 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 487 |Prior=129 [[F.2d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/129/24/1483387/ 24] ([[D.C. Cir.]] 1942) |Subsequent= |Holding=District of Columbia Court of Appeals decision reversed and remanded. |SCOTUS=1943-1945 |PerCuriam=yes |NotParticipating=Rutledge |LawsApplied= }}
'''''Busey v. District of Columbia''''', 319 U.S. 579 (1943), was a case in which the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] overturned the conviction of a [[Jehovah's Witness]] for unlicensed selling of magazines on public sidewalks.<ref>{{ussc|name=Busey v. District of Columbia|319|579|1943}}.</ref>
