{{Infobox |above = Hitler-Stalin Pact |bodystyle = width:19em |image1 = [[File:MolotovRibbentropStalin.jpg|220px]] |caption1 = Soviet Foreign Minister Vyacheslav Molotov signs the German–Soviet Pact in Moscow, September 28, 1939; behind him are Richard Schulze-Kossens (Ribbentrop's adjutant), Boris Shaposhnikov (Red Army Chief of Staff), Joachim von Ribbentrop, Joseph Stalin, Vladimir Pavlov (Soviet translator). Alexey Shkvarzev (Soviet ambassador in Berlin), stands next to Molotov |image2 = [[File:Mapa 2 paktu Ribbentrop-Mołotow.gif|220px]] |caption2 = Map attached to the German–Soviet Treaty dividing Poland into German and Soviet occupation zones }} The '''German–Soviet Frontier Treaty''' was a second supplementary protocol,<ref name="korman167">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=ueDO1dJyjrUC&pg=PA167&lpg=PA167&dq=German%20Soviet%20Frontier%20Treaty&f=false | title=The Right of Conquest : The Acquisition of Territory by Force in International Law and Practice | page=167 | publisher=Oxford University Press | ISBN=0191583804 | date=1996 | accessdate=25 April 2015 | author=Sharon Korman | quote=For the text of the ''German-Soviet Frontier Treaty'' see Degras, ''Soviet Documents on Foreign Policy'', iii. 377.}}</ref> of the [[Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact]] of 23 August.<ref>[[Norman Davies|Davies]] 2008, [https://books.google.ca/books?id=Jzxt9FFBDPwC&pg=PA30&lpg=PA30&dq=Norman+Davies,+German-Soviet+Treaty+Friendship+Demarcation&source=bl&ots=IoLgd2IoJD&sig=_Yba3ykOulctYjFLVqx4QfahRMQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=pW08VaXZO5fooATb9YC4DQ&ved=0CDMQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=Norman%20Davies%2C%20German-Soviet%20Treaty%20Friendship%20Demarcation&f=false page 30 (ibidem).]</ref> It was a secret clause as amended on September 28, 1939 by [[Nazi Germany]] and the [[Soviet Union]] after their [[invasion of Poland (1939)|joint invasion and occupation of sovereign Poland]].<ref name="davies1004">{{cite book |title=Europe: a History |last=Davies |first=Norman |authorlink=Norman Davies |year=2008 |orig-year=1996 |publisher=Oxford University Press, Pan Macmillan |location= |isbn=0-19-820171-0 |pages=1001, 1004 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jrVW9W9eiYMC&printsec=frontcover#v=snippet&q=German-Soviet%20Treaty%20Friendship%20Demarcation&f=false}}</ref> It was signed by [[Joachim von Ribbentrop]] and [[Vyacheslav Molotov]], the [[foreign minister]]s of Germany and the Soviet Union respectively, in the presence of Joseph Stalin. Only a small portion of the protocol, which superseded the first treaty, was publicly announced while the spheres of influence of Nazi Germany and the Soviet Union remained classified. The third secret protocol of the Pact was signed on January 10, 1941 by Friedrich Werner von Schulenberg, and Molotov, wherein Germany renounced its claims to portions of Lithuania, only a few months before their anti-Soviet [[Operation Barbarossa]].<ref name="britannica">{{cite web | url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/230972/German-Soviet-Nonaggression-Pact | title=A secret supplementary protocol (signed September 28, 1939) | publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica | work=German-Soviet Nonaggression Pact | date=2015 | accessdate=25 April 2015 | author=Britannica}}</ref>
==Secret articles== [[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-H27343, Dtsch.-Sowjet. Grenz- u. Freundschaftsvertrag.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Nazi Foreign Minister Joachim von Ribbentrop signs the German–Soviet Pact, September 28, 1939]] Several [[secret treaty|secret articles]] were attached to the treaty. These articles allowed for [[Nazi–Soviet population transfers|the exchange of Soviet and German nationals]] between the two occupied zones of Poland, redrew parts of the central European [[spheres of interest]] dictated by the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact, and also stated that neither party to the treaty would allow on its territory any "Polish agitation" directed at the other party.
During the western invasion of Poland, the German ''[[Wehrmacht]]'' had taken control of the [[Lublin Voivodeship (1919-1939)|Lublin Voivodeship]] and eastern [[Warsaw Voivodeship (1919-1939)|Warsaw Voivodeship]] - territories which according to the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact were in the Soviet sphere of influence. To compensate the Soviet Union for this "loss", the treaty's secret attachment transferred [[Lithuania]] to the Soviet sphere of influence, with the exception of a small territory in the [[Suwałki Region]], sometimes known as the Suwałki Triangle. After this transfer, the Soviet Union issued an [[1940 Soviet ultimatum to Lithuania|ultimatum to Lithuania]], occupied it on June 15, 1940 and established the [[Lithuanian SSR]].
